                <h3>In a nutshell . . .</h3>
                <div class="tools">
                    <p>A trademark identifies the source of goods or services, like the Nike swoosh. If you buy a pair of shoes with the swoosh on it,
                    you know they are Nikes. There is a difference between registering a trademark and owning a trademark. Trademarks are different from
                    copyrights and patents. A copyright protects duplication of books, music, artwork, and the like. A patent protects inventions. You
                    own a trademark once you use it in commerce, for example by putting it on a brochure or website. You register the trademark to put 
                    the entire country, and potentially most of the world on notice of your exclusive use rights. Trademarks are used for goods and
                    service marks for services. There is no functional difference between them. Registering a trademark protects in value as a brand 
                    identifier and makes it easier for you to protect your rights to the mark.</p>
