                <h3>Applying for registration . . .</h3>
                <div class="tools">
                    <p>You register a trademark by filing an application with the U.S. Patent & Trademark Office. Before submitting the
                    application, it should be reviewed to make sure (i) it can be registered and (ii) someone else hasn't already
                    registered it. Not all brand identifiers can be registered and there are numerous grounds for rejecting and application. 
                    For example, a mark that is merely descriptive of goods or services will not be accepted. Once it's determined that the mark
                    can be registered, the application is completed and filed. You must provide the USPTO with speciments and other relevant 
                    information. The application is assigned for review by an examining attornery who may accept it as is, ask for procedural
                    adjustments, or reject it on substantive grounds. If the application is accepted, the mark will be published in the
                    Official Register in case of public objection. Assuming there is no objection, the mark will be registered.</p>
